    id: 176,
    title: "“Fear of loss or death of understanding”",
    excerpt: "In the stillness of night, / when even the clock ticks in trembling breaths, / I wonder—",
    full: `In the stillness of night,
when even the clock ticks in trembling breaths,
I wonder—
was I afraid of losing him,
or afraid of losing myself
in his growing indifference?

He said, “Trust me,”
and I kept wondering—
how do you trust the man
who can dive into your eyes
and still never see the color of your tears?

Sometimes I thought I was wrong—
because I kept trying to make him understand,
but every attempt crashed
against the silent walls of his pride.
And he kept smiling,
as if my restlessness was his favorite show.

In the darkness of midnight,
when even the wind stops to hear me cry,
I ask myself—
was it wrong to fear losing him?
Or was he wrong
to mistake my fear for weakness?

He said, “You think too much.”
But how could I tell him—
it wasn’t my thoughts that haunted me,
it was the ghost of losing him
breathing in my chest every night.

Even now,
a scream hides somewhere inside me—
a scream that says,
“I only wanted to hold him close,
not lose myself to his silence.”

Maybe that’s the darkest truth of love—
it doesn’t always die,
sometimes… its understanding does.`,
