    id: 234,
    title: "Running Until Silence",
    excerpt: "I still don’t know / what I’m running from— / but the exhaustion in my bones",
    full: `I still don’t know
what I’m running from—
but the exhaustion in my bones
proves
that something has been chasing me
my entire life.

Sometimes I run from
the hollow promises of my own people,
words spoken loudly,
meant to sound permanent,
but empty enough
to collapse when I leaned on them.

Sometimes I run from
betrayal disguised as friendship—
a smile sharp enough
to cut deeper than hatred,
teaching me how to bleed
without making a sound.

Sometimes I run from
the grief given by those
who were supposed to protect me,
grief that never asked permission
before settling inside my chest
like an unpaid debt.

Sometimes I run from
the past—
those terrifying incidents
that ended years ago,
yet still breathe
inside my nightmares.

And sometimes,
I run from myself—
from the mistakes I made,
because forgiving myself
has always been harder
than blaming the world.

I keep running
because stopping asks questions,
and I only carry fear as answers.

There are moments
when my feet pause,
but the road never does.
I breathe,
yet peace refuses to follow.

I don’t know
when this running will end—
maybe when even exhaustion
gives up on me.

Maybe death
will be the first place
where I won’t need to escape,
because I lived my life
in constant motion,
and this
might be my only truth.

I ran my entire life—
and even death
didn’t grant me permission to stop.`,
