    id: 269,
    title: "Sometimes,",
    excerpt: "we step into other people’s stories, / thinking we belong there— / like a leaf carried by someone else’s wind.",
    full: `we step into other people’s stories,
thinking we belong there—
like a leaf carried by someone else’s wind.

But slowly, I learned:
the longer we stay in stories not our own,
the more we fade into the background,
becoming a quiet shadow on the edge of someone else’s light.

When we begin to write our own story,
life meets us gently—
like a river finally returning to its source,
like roots finding the soil meant for them.

Each time we choose others over ourselves,
something within us thins—
trust cracks like dry earth,
the heart bruises in silence,
the body remembers what the mouth never speaks.

But when we choose ourselves,
healing arrives softly.
Not like a storm,
but like rain after a long drought.
We begin to grow again.

Because we are the creators of our own seasons.
And when we learn to love ourselves,
we become like mountains—
quiet, grounded,
and unbreakable.`,
