    id: 308,
    title: "“One day, I will be there—",
    excerpt: "not in your calls, / not in your days, / but quietly… in the background of a memory",
    full: `not in your calls,
not in your days,
but quietly… in the background of a memory
you don’t visit anymore.

At first, you’ll remember me often,
in small things—
a song, a line, a habit I left behind.
You’ll smile… or maybe pause,
and say, “I knew someone like that once.”

But time is cruel in the softest ways.
It doesn’t snatch—
it slowly loosens the grip of everything
you thought you’d never forget.

Days will pass,
then months will blur into years,
and my name…
won’t come to your lips as easily.
You’ll search for it one day,
and realize—
it doesn’t echo the same anymore.

The memories will fade at the edges first,
like an old photograph losing its colors,
until even the moments we lived
start feeling like they belonged to someone else.

And one day,
there will be a day—
where I won’t exist in your mind at all.
No trace, no feeling, no shadow of me.

As if I was never there.
As if I never mattered.
As if time quietly erased me
without asking your permission.

Because that’s what memories do—
they don’t stay loyal forever.
They grow tired,
they slip,
they disappear.

And in the end,
we all become strangers again…
not by distance,
not by choice,
but by time.”`,
